{{Infobox language |name=Gutian |nativename=Qutian |region=[[Zagros Mountains]]? |ethnicity=[[Gutian people]] |era=[[Bronze Age]] ([[Early Bronze Age IV|EBA IV]]) |familycolor=unclassified |iso3=none |glotto=guti1235 |glottorefname=Gutian |glottofoot=no }}
'''Gutian''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|uː|t|i|ən}}; also '''Qutian''') is an extinct [[unclassified language]] that was spoken by the [[Gutian people]], who briefly ruled over [[Sumer]] as the [[Gutian dynasty of Sumer|Gutian dynasty]] in the 22nd century BCE ([[middle chronology]]). The Gutians lived in the territory between the [[Zagros Mountains]] and the [[Tigris]]. Nothing is known about the language except its existence and a list of names of Gutian rulers in the [[Sumerian King List]].
== Evidence == Gutian is included in a list of languages spoken in the region found in the ''Sag'' B tablet, an educational text from the Middle Babylonian period possibly originating from the city of [[Emar]].<ref name="heimpel">{{cite book | first = Wolfgang | last = Heimpel | title = Letters to the King of Mari | publisher = Eisenbrauns | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-1-57506-080-4 | page = 13 }}</ref> This text also lists [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]], [[Amorite language|Amorite]], [[Sutean language|Sutean]], "[[Subartu|Subarean]]" ([[Hurrian language|Hurrian]]) and [[Elamite language|Elamite]]. There is also a mention of "an interpreter for the Gutean language" in a tablet from [[Adab (city)|Adab]].<ref name="wilcke">{{cite book | first = Claus | last = Wilcke | title = Early Ancient Near Eastern Law: A History of Its Beginnings : the Early Dynastic and Sargonic Periods | publisher = Eisenbrauns | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-1-57506-132-0 | page = 50 }}</ref>
The Gutian king names from the Sumerian list are:<ref>{{cite web | title = The Sumerian king list | work = The Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature | publisher = Faculty of Oriental Studies, University of Oxford | at = 308–334 | url = http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.2.1.1#t211.p18 }}</ref> {{div col|colwidth=15em}} * ''[[Inkishush|Inkišuš]]'' * ''[[Zarlagab]]'' * ''[[Shulme|Šulme]]'' (or ''Yarlagaš'') * ''[[Elulmesh|Silulumeš]]'' (or ''Silulu'') * ''[[Inimabakesh|Inimabakeš]]'' (or ''Duga'') * ''[[Igeshaush|Igešauš]]'' (or ''Ilu-An'') * ''[[Yarlagab]]'' * ''[[Ibate]]'' * ''[[Yarla]]'' (or ''Yarlangab'') * ''[[Kurum]]'' * ''[[Apilkin]]'' * ''[[La-erabum|Lā-erabum]]'' * ''[[Irarum]]'' * ''[[Ibranum]]'' * ''[[Hablum]]'' * ''[[Puzur-Suen]]'' * ''[[Yarlaganda]]'' * ''[[Tirigan]]'' {{div col end}} [[Thorkild Jacobsen]] suggested that the recurring ending ''-(e)š'' may have had a grammatical function in Gutian, perhaps as a [[grammatical case|case]] marker.<ref>{{cite book | first = Thorkild | last = Jacobsen | author-link = Thorkild Jacobsen | title = The Sumerian King List | publisher = University of Chicago Press | orig-year = 1939 | year = 1973 | isbn = 0-226-62273-8 | at = p. 207, n. 40 | url = https://oi.uchicago.edu/pdf/as11.pdf }}</ref>
== Tocharian theory == In a posthumously-published article, [[W. B. Henning]] suggested that the different endings of the king names resembled [[grammatical case|case]] endings in the [[Tocharian languages]], a branch of [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] known from texts found in the [[Tarim Basin]] (in the northwest of modern China) dating from the 6th to 8th centuries CE.<ref name="Henning">{{cite book | first = W.B. | last = Henning | author-link = Walter Bruno Henning | chapter = The first Indo-Europeans in history | pages = 215–230 | title = Society and History, Essays in Honour of Karl August Wittfogel | editor-first = G.L. | editor-last = Ulmen | location = The Hague | publisher = Mouton | year = 1978 | isbn = 978-90-279-7776-2 }}</ref> Henning also compared the name Guti with ''Kuči'', the native name of the Tocharian city of [[Kucha]], and with the name of the [[Yuezhi]], [[pastoral nomads]] described in Chinese records as living to the east of the Tarim in the 2nd century BCE,<ref name="Henning"/> although the latter name is usually reconstructed with a *ŋʷ- initial in [[Old Chinese]].<ref>{{cite book | title = A Handbook of Old Chinese Phonology | first = William H. | last = Baxter | author-link = William H. Baxter | location = Berlin | publisher = Mouton de Gruyter | year = 1992 | isbn = 978-3-11-012324-1 | page = 806 }}</ref> He also compared ''Tukriš'', the name of neighbours of the Guti, with the name ''twγry'' found in [[Old Turkic language|Old Turkish]] manuscripts from the early 9th century CE and thought to refer to the Tocharians.<ref name="Henning"/> [[Tamaz V. Gamkrelidze|Gamkrelidze]] and [[Vyacheslav Ivanov (philologist)|Ivanov]] explored Henning's suggestion as possible support for their proposal of an [[Proto-Indo-European Urheimat hypotheses|Indo-European Urheimat]] in the [[Near East]].<ref>{{cite journal | first1 = T.V. | last1 = Gamkrelidze | author-link1 = Tamaz V. Gamkrelidze | first2 = V.V. | last2 = Ivanov | author-link2 = Vyacheslav Ivanov (philologist) | title = Первые индоевропейцы на арене истории: прототохары в Передней Азии |trans-title= The first Indo-Europeans in history: the proto-Tocharians in the Near East | journal = [[Journal of Ancient History]] | year = 1989 | number = 1 | pages = 14–39 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | first1 = T.V. | last1 = Gamkrelidze | first2 = V.V. | last2 = Ivanov | title = Индоевропейская прародина и расселение индоевропейцев: полвека исследований и обсуждений |trans-title= Indo-European homeland and migrations: half a century of studies and discussions | journal = Journal of Language Relationship | year = 2013 | volume = 9 | pages = 109–136 | url = http://www.jolr.ru/article.php?id=110 }}</ref> However, most scholars reject the attempt to compare languages separated by more than two millennia.<ref>{{cite book | title = The Tarim Mummies | first1 = J.P. | last1 = Mallory | author1-link = J. P. Mallory | first2 = Victor H. | last2 = Mair | author2-link = Victor H. Mair | location = London | publisher = Thames & Hudson | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-500-05101-6 | pages = 281–282 }}</ref>
