{{Infobox language |name=Mednyj Aleut |states=[[Russia]] |region=[[Commander Islands]] |speakers= 350 |date=2010 |ref=<ref name="e20">{{e20|mud|Aleut, Mednyj}}</ref> |familycolor=Mixed |family=[[mixed language|mixed]] [[Aleut language|Aleut]]–[[Russian language|Russian]] |iso3=mud |glotto=medn1235 |glottorefname=Mednyj Aleut }}
'''Mednyj Aleut''' (also called '''Copper Island [[Creole language|Creole]]''' or '''Copper Island Aleut''') is a nearly extinct [[mixed language]] spoken on [[Bering Island]]. It is characterized by [[Aleut language|Aleut]] nouns and [[Russian language|Russian]] verbs, each with the full inflectional complexity of the source languages. There are only five native speakers left.
Mednyj Aleut is characterised by a blending of Russian and Aleut (primarily [[Attu Island|Attu]]) elements in most components of the grammar, but most profoundly in the verbal morphology. The Aleut component comprises the majority of the vocabulary, all the derivational morphology, part of the simple sentence syntax, nominal inflection and certain other grammatical means. The Russian components comprise verbal inflection, negation, infinitive forms, part of the simple sentence syntax and all of the compound sentence syntax.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lc1DFju-FlYC&dq=An+Introduction+to+Contact+Linguistics&hl=en&sa=X&ei=20o5UeqnA8XT0wGg2oHgDQ&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA|title=An Introduction to Contact Linguistics|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|author=Donald Winford|accessdate=}}</ref>
Originally, the language was spoken on [[Medny Island|Copper Island]], from where it takes its name, but all the population of that island was moved to Bering island in 1970.
